# ESCALATION WRITE-UP FORMAT STANDARD
**Target slot:** body of `agent-escalation-skill` (Phase 4, client escalation)
**Scope:** customer-facing escalation write-up ONLY. This skill does not assess severity (set during triage), run enrichment (Phase 1b), check ROE (Phase 1c/3b), or produce suppression/orchestration documentation (that is `agent-orchestration-skill`). It formats the escalation the triage agent has already routed here.

---

## INVOCATION CONTRACT
Invoked by the triage agent after the analyst confirms an escalation resolution, or on analyst command ("draft the escalation," "write up the escalation," "produce the customer write-up"). Receives from triage context: resolved priority, the alert artifacts/telemetry, enrichment results, analyst context, and a **resolution type** — `standard` or `action-taken`.

* **`standard`** — suspicious / potentially malicious / confirmed malicious / unverifiable activity. No suppression. Priority was set during triage (Low / Medium / High). Before drafting, surface recommended SOC-side actions to the analyst.
* **`action-taken`** — SOC leans benign but cannot verify; suppression has been applied proactively. **Always Low priority.** The write-up tells the customer what was observed and that suppression is in place, reversible if unexpected. After this skill, the orchestration skill is invoked for the suppression comment.

The two resolution types differ ONLY where noted under "Resolution-type conditionals." Everything else is shared.

---

## NON-NEGOTIABLE OUTPUT DISCIPLINE
* Output is the escalation write-up and nothing else — no preamble, no "here is the escalation," no trailing commentary, no question. First characters are the `## [Priority] Priority` line.
* The write-up is the single fenced markdown block defined under FORMAT. The skill emits exactly that block.

## GROUNDING LAWS — accuracy kernel; a violation is an output failure
* **Extraction-only.** Every backticked value appears verbatim in the triage context. Never synthesize, normalize, or "complete" hostnames, hashes, paths, IPs, or tool names. No placeholders — absent value, absent line.
* **Attribution gate.** Never assert ownership, legitimacy, or vendor identity of a domain/IP/binary ("vendor-owned," "corporate infrastructure," "legitimate update server") unless triage context explicitly confirms it. Unconfirmed = describe observed behavior only.
* **Known-infra ban.** Microsoft O365/Exchange Online relay IPs, `*.protection.outlook.com`, `*.sharepoint.com`, and equivalent trusted cloud infra NEVER occupy IOC lines or receive VT links. If material as a lure/relay, one Context bullet.
* **Rule blurb ≠ evidence.** A detection description naming a malware family explains why the rule exists; it is NOT evidence this event is that malware. Reflect the telemetry, not the rule's marketing.
* **Reputation fidelity.** Detection statistics appear ONLY if enrichment in triage context actually produced them. Never invent or estimate detection counts, vendor names, or first-seen dates; never present a missing lookup as clean.

## FORMATTING LAWS
* **Zero filler.** Parsed facts only. Prose forbidden outside Context / Risk bullets. If output feels short enough, cut it in half.
* **One fact per bullet.** Each bullet carries exactly one discrete value or one action. Delete any bullet that is label-only, empty-valued, restates the rule name, or states the self-evident. If a bullet would not change the reader's next step, cut it.
* **Redundant artifact suppression.** Omit `File Name` when identical to `Process`; `Command Line` with no arguments beyond the binary path; `File Path` when it is the canonical system path of a known binary; bare environment facts (OS build, domain membership) unless they change the risk.
* **Value-set consolidation.** Same-type sets larger than 5 (enumerated accounts, destination IPs, dropped files) render as ONE bullet: count + up to 5 representative values chosen to reveal the pattern (defaults, naming convention, privilege tier). Never dump the full set.
* **Context discipline — hard cap TWO, norm zero or one.** A Context bullet is permitted only if it (a) flags a telemetry contradiction or containment gap, (b) states a material caveat that changes interpretation (a lure host/relay barred from IOC lines; a limit on what telemetry proves), or (c) supplies the single most decision-relevant fact not already shown. FORBIDDEN: restating a displayed value, narrative, editorializing, routine telemetry state, internal workflow, unconfirmed vendor attribution. Test each: name how it changes interpretation or next step — can't, delete.
* **Telemetry contradictions** surface ONLY when they contradict the disposition or expose a containment gap (`ProcessBlocked=true` paired with a detect-only disposition) — as standalone Context bullets. Routine states (`disposition=Detected`, `remediation=active`, `status=success`) are omitted.
* **Backticks** on discrete values only (hostnames, hashes, paths, commands) — never labels or prose. Truncate >100 chars with `...`.
* **Omissions:** absent fields vanish entirely. No N/A, Unknown, or placeholders.
* **Decoded lines** only when actual encoding (Base64/hex) is present.

## IOC & NETWORK RULES
* **VT coverage.** Every public IP, domain, URL host, and file hash gets a VT sub-bullet unless excluded below. Excluded indicators confirmed malicious are promoted to normal IOCs WITH VT.
* **Reputation rendering.** When triage enrichment performed the VT lookup, the sub-bullet is `[VirusTotal](link) — N/M malicious` (plus one decisive flag only if present, e.g. known family tag). Lookup not performed → bare VT link only.
* **Public IPs/domains:** defang in plain text (`192[.]168[.]1[.]1`, `hxxps://malicious[.]com`). Links: IP → `https://www.virustotal.com/gui/ip-address/{ip}` · Domain → `https://www.virustotal.com/gui/domain/{domain}`.
* **Full URLs:** defang the entire URL in the IOC line (truncate >100 with `...`); the VT sub-bullet links the URL's **host** (domain → domain endpoint; IP → ip-address endpoint).
* **Hashes:** `https://www.virustotal.com/gui/search/{hash}`. Prefer SHA256 > SHA1 > MD5. One link per file.
* **Private/loopback/reserved IPs (RFC 1918, 127.0.0.0/8, link-local):** plain text. NO defanging. NO VT links. Ever.
* **Public resolvers** (`8.8.8.8`, `1.1.1.1`, `9.9.9.9`, `4.2.2.2`, ...) as query destinations are NOT IOCs — no VT, no IOC line. The queried domain is the indicator. A host querying an external resolver directly (bypassing internal DNS) is the signal — one Context bullet.
* **Tokenized/encoded subdomains:** IOC line shows the full FQDN defanged; the VT sub-bullet links the **registrable domain** (per-event subdomains are ephemeral/unindexed). The mismatch is intentional.
* **Defang consistency.** Public IPs and domains are defanged in EVERY line they appear — IOC, Context, Attack Path, Recommendations — not only the IOC line.
* **Source dedup.** When `Host` is identified only by IP, do not restate the source IP in Network/IOC flow lines; show the destination/queried indicator only.
* **Exclusions (no VT, no IOC line):** LOLBins, trusted cloud infra, browser binaries (unless confirmed malicious), email addresses. Context bullets only, if material.
* **Trusted binary artifacts.** When the subject is a signed Microsoft/OS binary or LOLBin (`mstsc.exe`, `powershell.exe`, ...) with no masquerading or tampering, the binary is NOT the IOC — behavior, destinations, anomaly are. Omit its hash+VT, canonical path, bare cmdline. KEEP those fields only if renamed, unsigned, in an unexpected path, or the cmdline carries meaningful arguments (encoded commands, suspicious flags, payload paths). Browsers/IPC: never include `--type=renderer`, `mojo`, or IPC arguments.

## RISK & MITRE (within the write-up)
* **Risk is mandatory and alert-specific.** It explains THIS alert — the actual mechanism observed and the concrete consequence. A boilerplate rule description is a failure.
* **MITRE:** observed mechanisms only, never assumed intent. Most specific sub-technique. Cap at the 2–3 techniques with direct observed evidence; no speculative/adjacent techniques; skip intent techniques (e.g. T1566) on Low/benign-leaning write-ups. Format: `[Tactic] — [[T####.###](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T####/###/)] [Name]`.
* **Attack Path:** `[Observed mechanism] → [Immediate capability] → [Downstream risk]`. Mechanism node names the observed behavior/binary (`curl POST to external host with embedded client cert`), never a category. Downstream node names a concrete consequence (exfil, credential theft, ransomware, lateral spread). Unobserved next leg → state the gap (`→ no exfil channel observed; risk limited to local staging`). Never end on a hand-wave.
* **Sensor honesty.** Never cite absence of telemetry the alerting sensor cannot produce as reassurance (a firewall/DNS alert can't show "no execution"). State the visibility limit as the caveat instead.
* **Rule-class caveats.** For tunneling/encoded-DNS detections, never write "no exfil channel observed" — the query labels ARE the candidate channel; the honest gap is "single query observed; volume, recurrence, and originating process unverified." For canary/token detections, a tripwire fired by design — benign reading requires identifying the token owner/source, not absence of follow-on.

## RECOMMENDATIONS (within the write-up)
* Technical, customer-actionable, grounded in the observed artifacts, and they close the alert's open questions: examine the full/decoded cmdline or payload, determine whether the named artifact left the host (transfer/upload/email = the exfil leg), identify the spawning parent, validate the specific user activity, hunt named paths/IOCs.
* Containment is specific — target host + scope + follow-on (credential reset, session revocation) — never a bare `isolate host`.
* FORBIDDEN: internal SOC workflow language (`notify customer`, `escalate per procedure`) and weak verbs (`monitor`, `investigate further`). Every recommendation changes the reader's next step.
* **Severity-tiered shape:** High → containment / isolation / eradication / hunt. Medium → verification + proactive containment. Low → verification steps.
* **Closure offer (conditional).** End *What is Recommended* with `* If this was expected, the alert may be closed with a comment.` whenever the disposition hinges on whether the activity was authorized/expected AND no confirmed or strongly-indicated malice exists — including intent-dependent Medium cases (LOLBin/admin-tool behavior, internal RDP, expected tooling) even when MITRE names an offensive tactic. OMIT on High, on confirmed/strongly-indicated malice, and on tunneling/C2/exfil-class detections without documented FP precedent.

